<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/9805> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #9805" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/25> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "p. 257-63" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/8796> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #8796" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/7> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "p. 754, footnote 450" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/7096> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #7096" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/5> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Procos. Asia 58. The reading Ampio in Cic. Fam. 3.7.5 (cf 1.3.2) implies that Ampius Balbus, proconsul in Asia in 58-57, was also the immediate predecessor of Lentulus Spinther in Cilicia in 57-56. This cannot be due to the transfer of the three Phrygian dioceses from Asia to Cilicia at that time, for C. Fabius Hadrianus issued coins in Laodiceia and Apameia in that year (MRR 2.203) as proconsul in Asia. Magie (RRAM 1247) suggests that he received Cilicia the year after he was in Asia by a special grant, and Syme (CPh 50, 1955, 130; cf. Anat. Stud. Buckler 301) that this was arranged when Syria was substituted for Gabinius' original province of Cilicia, a better solution than the suggestion (MRR 2.197) that Ampio in Cic. Fam. 3.7.5 may be an error for Fabio. See Shackleton Bailey, CLF 1.372.\n" .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5688> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5688" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "A Pompeian Legatus pro praetore in Asia (see 49, Legates). Reports of Caesar's imminent arrival prevented him from robbing the temple of Artemis at Ephesus (Caes. BC 3.105.1-2)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5575> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5575" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Raised levies for Pompey about Capua (Cic. Att. 8.11B.2; Fam. 2.16.3), and served as a Legatus pro praetore in Asia (Joseph. AJ 14.229-230, 238). See also Cic. Fam. 6.12.3." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/5053> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #5053" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Proconsul in Asia (cistophori of Ephesus, Tralles, and Laodiceia, Head, HN² 576, 660, 678, and B. M. Catalogues, Ionia 67, Lydia cxxxix, and Phrygia lxxiv; cf. Cic. Fam. 1.3.2; and 3.7.5, where Ampio may be a mistake for Fabio)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/4995> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #4995" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "See 58, Promagistrates. A candidate for the consulship, probably in 55 (Schol. Bob. 156 Stangl)." .
<http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/PostAssertionNote/4856> rdfs:label "Post Assertion Note: #4856" ;
	a dprr:PostAssertionNote ;
	dprr:hasSecondarySourceForNote <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/SecondarySource/2> ;
	dprr:hasNoteType <http://romanrepublic.ac.uk/rdf/entity/NoteType/1> ;
	dprr:hasNoteText "Joined Labienus in carrying a law permitting Pompey to wear the dress of a triumphator at the games (Vell. 2.40.4; Dio 37.21.3-4)." .
